ire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"1365–1395":"1365–1395","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1336–Female":"1336–Deceased","1373–1436":"1373–1436","1389–1445":"1389–1445","1335–1397":"1335–1397","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1436":"1436","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","1445":"1445","1389":"1389","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","1397":"1397","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England":"Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England","married 1389 in Landwade, Cambridge, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Cotton Hall, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cotton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called from Old English <i>(æt) cotum</i> (dative plural of <i>cot</i>) ‘at the cottages or huts’ (or sometimes possibly from a Middle English plural, <i>coten</i>). Examples include Coton (Cambridgeshire, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire), Cottam (East Yorkshire, Lancashire, Nottinghamshire), and Cotham (Nottinghamshire). Particularly common in Staffordshire.","French: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  ), derived via <i>Nicot</i>, or of the personal name   Jacques  , derived via <i>Jacot</i>.","History: John Cotton (1584–1652) was a noted Puritan preacher, who landed at Boston, MA, from London in 1633 and became leader of the Congregationalists in America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cotten","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cotton  .","Altered form of German <b>Kotten</b>, a habitational name from any of several places so named in Rhineland, Westphalia, Silesia, etc., or perhaps an American shortened form of composite German surnames such as <b>Kottenhagen</b>, <b>Kottenhoff</b>, <b>Kottenkamp</b> (see   Koth  )."]},{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Cotham","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottom","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottam","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): variant of   Cotton  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Cotton was born in 1365, in Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England, his father, Knight Thomas Cotton Sr., was 30 and his mother, Alice De Hastings, was 25. He married Bridgett Grace in 1389, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1395, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1365–1395":"1365–1395","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1336–Female":"1336–Surnud","1373–1436":"1373–1436","1389–1445":"1389–1445","1335–1397":"1335–1397","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1436":"1436","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","1445":"1445","1389":"1389","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","1397":"1397","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England":"Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England","married 1389 in Landwade, Cambridge, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cotton Hall, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"1365–1395":"1365–1395","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1336–Female":"1336–Kuollut","1373–1436":"1373–1436","1389–1445":"1389–1445","1335–1397":"1335–1397","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1436":"1436","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","1445":"1445","1389":"1389","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","1397":"1397","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England":"Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England","married 1389 in Landwade, Cambridge, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cotton Hall, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fr":{"1365–1395":"1365–1395","1365–F